a1e567dd241ac21fab4fc0d1e4d51343.description: SUMMARY: On January 20, 2016, Billy Blattner, Manager of Regulatory Relations, San Diego Gas & Electric Company (SDG&E), met with Matthew Tisdale, advisor to Cmmr. Florio, and David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in two separate meetings in San Francisco.  At the meeting with David Gamson also present was Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman.  Dan Skopec, Vice President of Regulatory Affairs for SDG&E, participated in both meetings.  Blattner stated that SDG&E's Vehicle-Grid Integration (VGI) proposal and settlement were designed to be responsive to state policies and Commission guidance.  Blattner expressed concern that the Proposed Decision does not clearly provide for ongoing operations and maintenance.   Skopec indicated that such costs should be recorded and recovered in future rate proceedings.  Blattner stated that parties who claim that the model is invalid because it uses illustrative data are creating a Catch-22 where a program cannot be approved without data, but data cannot be generated without a program. Blattner also suggested that the proposed customer segment and location quotas are inconsistent with prior Commission guidance. In the meeting with Tisdale, Blattner also explained that demand response is essentially embedded within the VGI rate which benefits all ratepayers.

98d818e1acb40e74cc7cd92d661cc8de.description: SUMMARY: On Friday, January 8, 2016, Aaron Johnson, Vice President, Customer Energy Solutions Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), met with Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco. Also present were David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman; and Jana Corey, Director, Electrification and Alternative Fuels, and Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, for PG&E. Johnson explained that a diversity of approaches to electric vehicle (EV) charging infrastructure is appropriate. Corey described PG&E’s EV infrastructure and education program design, and stated that PG&E is carefully following the policy language found in the proposed and alternative proposed decisions on SCE’s and SDG&E’s EV applications. Corey described PG&E’s DC fast charger proposal. Johnson stated that restrictive allocations of EV charger site locations, like a 50/50 split between workplaces and multi-unit dwellings, would be difficult to implement and could slow the deployment of needed EV chargers. Johnson stated that more EV pilots are not needed. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.
